{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646792"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:35:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18207"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18207"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60404"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1528"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5284"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn areas where malaria remains sensitive to chloroquines, hydroxychloroquine is used to prevent and treat malaria. It is also used to treat other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is hydroxychloroquine most appropriately used for?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Osteoarthritis","Gout","Psoriatic arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where hydroxychloroquine is commonly used due to its ability to reduce disease activity and prevent flares. It is particularly effective in managing skin and joint manifestations and has a favourable safety profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can be treated with hydroxychloroquine, but it is not the first-line treatment and is usually used in combination with other disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically treated with hydroxychloroquine, as other DMARDs and biologics are preferred due to their efficacy in controlling both skin and joint symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a degenerative joint disease that does not benefit from hydroxychloroquine, as it does not have an inflammatory component that would respond to this medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E is managed with medications that lower uric acid levels or reduce inflammation during acute attacks, such as colchicine or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, rather than hydroxychloroquine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydroxychloroquine is commonly used in the management of systemic lupus erythematosus due to its immunomodulatory effects.","Hydroxychloroquine is not typically used for psoriatic arthritis, where other disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs are preferred."],"references":["Bansal P, Goyal A, Cusick A 4th, Lahan S, Dhaliwal HS, Bhyan P, Bhattad PB, Aslam F, Ranka S, Dalia T, Chhabra L, Sanghavi D, Sonani B, Davis JM 3rd. Hydroxychloroquine: a comprehensive review and its controversial role in coronavirus disease 2019. Ann Med. 2021 Dec;53(1):117-134. doi: 10.1080/07853890.2020.1839959. PMID: 33095083; PMCID: PMC7880079.","Dima, A., Jurcut, C., \u0026 Arnaud, L. (2021). Hydroxychloroquine in systemic and autoimmune diseases: where are we now?. Joint Bone Spine, 88(3), 105143.","Padda IS, Goyal A. Leflunomide. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491731","Tian H, Cronstein BN. Understanding the mechanisms of action of methotrexate: implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. Bull NYU Hosp Jt Dis. 2007;65(3):168-73. PMID: 17922664","Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18207"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T09:31:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T09:32:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"